            "key": "04_faq_block",
            "body_en": "## **From the government partner, what information is needed to get started? **\n\n1. **Content:** To configure the public-facing website, we need to know the needs of the target population you want to serve and the information you need to gather to be able to help them. This will allow us to design forms tailored to your needs. Simply by editing the text fields in Airtable, we can update most of the website’s text fields and form request fields.\n2. **Steward:** For sustained management of the back office platform, we ask partners to identify a steward of the program. Is Neighbor Express something you want to lead within the city or have a third-party organization lead? Airtable offers multiple levels of permissions for viewing and editing to support this. We’ll update this section once you have decided how to staff your team and what levels of access you want to provide to each partner.\n3. **Technology Subscription(s)**: The only costs associated with Neighbor Express stem from the tool subscriptions we strongly recommend. The estimated cost for a monthly subscription to Airtable is $20. We will configure the back-office data management platform for you and then support your team as they transition to manage it.\n\n## **When adopting Neighbor Express for our community, who is responsible for what component in the full implementation model? **\n### **NEx Team: **\n\n- We’ll launch a **public-facing website** and **back office** in full. We will then transition the working site to your team and provide instructions on how to adapt content and manage the volunteer system via Airtable. \n\n### **Government Partner:**\n\n- Long-term management of the back office data platform to be used for collecting form responses as well as matching volunteers and assistance requests \n- Contact information for a program steward to field questions from community members\n- Subscription of associated technology\n\n## **How are payments processed?  **\nCities who are currently using Neighbor Express have used the following options: \n\n1. **Call the store in advance.** If the Neighbor Express program in your area partners with specific grocery stores, the homebound individual has the ability to place an order and pay over the phone in advance. \n2. **Reimburse you after you pick up their items. **The recipient pays you back via a digital payment app (Venmo, PayPal, etc). If the recipient doesn’t want to use one of those apps, or can’t, etc, they can also make out a check to _you_ after you know the order total, and leave it for you to collect at their door once you’ve (safely!) delivered their groceries. \n\nWe are constantly seeing iterations of solutions to this and will continue updating as more governments come onboard. In case of a problem, some cities have received donations which they can use as emergency funds to repay volunteers in the event payment falls through. \n\n\n## **What systems are in place to protect the data that is inputted when a request is made on the online portal? **\nWe suggest limiting the information you gather to data that is publicly available and absolutely required. Our templates include name, email, address, and phone number and specifically do not ask for payment information or sensitive records/IDs. This minimizes the risk that sensitive data could be accidentally disclosed. Furthermore, Airtable offers multiple levels of permissions for viewing and editing. We’ll update this section with further suggestions on how to staff your team and what levels of access you can provide.\n\n## **Is there a process for vetting volunteers? If so, what is it?**\nWe recommend that your team consider the specific risk in your community and design your own process for validating volunteers. By default, the Neighbor Express system includes the ability to mark and filter volunteers as High Trust, Trust, Low Trust, and not yet vetted. In order to make this determination, we utilize criteria that is provided by our government partner. If you have other ideas for features or ways we can use technology to mitigate risk and likelihood of scams, please let us know. For example, we are using the social profile of a potential volunteer and past volunteer records to determine trustworthiness in a city in California. \n\nWe have also seen other jurisdictions partner with a community based partner to enable them to start using Neighbor Express right away with a pre-vetted list of volunteers. Their volunteer sign-up form continues to collect new volunteers, and they are partnering with Sterling to complete background checks. \n",
